helpdesk-ticket.subject: Virus Scanning Software?
helpdesk-ticket.description: What is the virus protection software on the MSOE-issued laptops, and how do I launch the software and run a scan? I installed a bunch of software yesterday and would just feel better if I ran a hard disk scan.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: What is the virus protection software on the MSOE-issued laptops, and how do I launch the software and run a scan? I installed a bunch of software yesterday and would just feel better if I ran a hard disk scan.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Jeffrey Rolland, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9314 We use Microsoft endpoint security on our laptops. The security and scans run in the background without any sort of user interaction, and does not provide a manual disk check option. Any detected issues are handled internally by windows. We will send out an email if we decide to deploy any further antivirus options such as ESET. Have a nice day.
Thanks,
Cameron Wilson Information Technology
Assistant System Admin 414-277-7288 helpdesk@msoe.edu
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Jeffrey Rolland,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9314
We use Microsoft endpoint security on our laptops. The security and scans run in the background without any sort of user interaction, and does not provide a manual disk check option. Any detected issues are handled internally by windows. We will send out an email if we decide to deploy any further antivirus options such as ESET.
Have a nice day.


Thanks,

Cameron Wilson
Information Technology
Assistant System Admin

helpdesk-ticket.subject: FW: We need to see if MS is still having a problem
helpdesk-ticket.description:
[SUBJECT] Information Technology - Secure Email Tips
[INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY HEADER]
Recently, there has been an increase in malicious email and phishing attempts. MSOE has safeguards in place for the most common dangers, but there are steps you can take to better protect yourself, your data, and MSOE.
Beware of Phishing Phishing is an attempt to disguise a malicious email as a legitimate email to trick you into clicking a link or providing secure information, such as your user ID or password.
· Be suspicious of unusual wording, grammar, or poor spelling
· Look for intentional misspellings in the URL
· Verify that the links in the email point to legitimate URLs. Hover over the link to check
Example: Reset Your Password<dont.click.me.Im.malicious.edu> (dont.click.me.Im.malicious.edu)
Beware of Malware Malware may be an attachment that could damage your computer or allow remote access.
· Don't open attachments from addresses you don't trust
· Be careful if an attachment asks you to enable macros or to make changes to your computer
· Look for suspicious or vague email subject lines and attachment names
Examples: For Your Review, The Document You Requested, invoice.docx
Trust Your Instincts If something seems suspicious to you, it probably is. You can always open a ticket to the Helpdesk (helpdesk@msoe.edu<mailto:helpdesk@msoe.edu>) and we can review the email. If you find malicious email that bypassed the safeguards in place, we can delete the email from all recipients it was sent to. Use your best judgement, and err on the side of caution.
For more information, please contact the Helpdesk
No MSOE employee nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask for your account password.
[HELPDESK FOOTER]

No MSOE employee nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask for your account password.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Tyler Braun, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9350
This is due to your laptop not connecting to our network. There are two possible ways to correct this issue. The first option is to bring your laptop onto the MSOE campus and connect to an ethernet cord before rebooting the computer and signing in with the new password. After this has happened make sure to shut down while still plugged in to the ethernet. The other option is to login to the computer with the old password, and connect to the school network using GlobalProtect. Once the connection has been completed, simply lock the computer by pressing the windows key and the L key at the same time and login with the new password. Using these instructions, were you able to login to the laptop with the new password?
Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-ticket.subject: malicious website?
helpdesk-ticket.description: Im out of town and was looking for oil change price at jiffy lube and got a ransom note/message from a site. It seems that i can't run the virus scan included on our computers, any recommendations.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: Im out of town and was looking for oil change price at jiffy lube and got a ransom note/message from a site. It seems that i can't run the virus scan included on our computers, any recommendations.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi unserj, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9353
Im out of town and was looking for oil change price at jiffy lube and got a ransom note/message from a site. It seems that i can't run the virus scan included on our computers, any recommendations.
My guess is that a javascript hack is popping up a scare message. Don't call them or give any information out. The short answer to solve this hack is to turn off your network access by disabling wireless and unplugging any ethernet cable. force close your browser from task manager. the scare message should still be there but now you will be able to close it. x off the scare message. Turn your network back on. Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi unserj,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9353

Im out of town and was looking for oil change price at jiffy lube and got a ransom note/message from a site. It seems that i can't run the virus scan included on our computers, any recommendations.

My guess is that a javascript hack is popping up a scare message.  Don't call them or give any information out.  The short answer to solve this hack is to turn off your network access by disabling wireless and unplugging any ethernet cable.  force close your browser from task manager.  the scare message should still be there but now you will be able to close it.  x off the scare message.  Turn your network back on.

Peter Pfister
Help Desk Coordinator
414.277.7202

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Voice-mail box full
helpdesk-ticket.description: User says he deleted all voice-mails from his voice-mail box but he still gets a message for voice-mail box being full
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: User says he deleted all voice-mails from his voice-mail box but he still gets a message for voice-mail box being full

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sheku,
When you deleted the voicemails did you use ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu? If so did you delete them from the deleted items folder? There is no security certificate on the server for the web server so you will have to click around it. it is covered in step one and 2 of these directions.
1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome 2. Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….” 3. Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password. 4. Click web inbox 5. Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages. 6. Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder. 7. Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window. 8. Give it a minute and it should clear up space.
9. You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.4
Let me know if this helps.
Tony
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Sheku,

When you deleted the voicemails did you use ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu? If so did you delete them from the deleted items folder? There is no security certificate on the server for the web server so you will have to click around it. it is covered in step one and 2 of these directions.

1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome
2. Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….”
3. Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password.
4. Click web inbox
5. Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages.
6. Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder.
7. Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window.
8. Give it a minute and it should clear up space.
9. You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.4

Let me know if this helps.

Tony

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sheku,
It looks like you are just out of the quota now. It was at 37 messages and 13.7mB when i looked before now at 25 messages its at 10.4mB which is close to the warning limit of 11mB.
I will bump your box size and we will see if that resolves the issue.
Tony

helpdesk-note.body:
This is a message for Thomas related to the incident listed above. The problem involves getting a “Page Expired” message when trying to login. I initially noticed it with Outlook, but have now observed it with the other Office programs and Box so I think it may be a single sign in issue. Keep in mind I’m using Windows 10.
It had not occurred for over a week, but today I changed my MSOE password (only because it was about to expire) and the problem started again. Here are the details as best as I can recall them. I did the pw change while at home but with a VPN connection using GlobalProtect. The pw change went smoothly and I continued to work without problems for about 8 hours. I then got a message while using Outlook indicating I needed to login and when I entered my username and pw, I got the “Page Expired” dialog. It is possible that I lost my VPN connection just before Outlook prompted me to login again. I exited Outlook and restarted it. I got a need password notification and again got the “Page Expired” dialog when I entered my credentials. I exited Outlook, went into Credential Manager and deleted my Microsoft credentials, restarted Outlook, entered my credentials and got the “Page Expired” dialog. I then exited Outlook, went into Credential Manager and deleted my Office related credentials (there were about 6 of them), restarted Outlook, entered my credentials and got the “Page Expired” dialog. I exited Outlook and all other open program and restated my computer. I then restarted Outlook, entered my credentials and got the “Page Expired” dialog. In the process of restarting my computer I got a login message from Box Sync and when I tried to login using single sign-in I got the “Page Expired” dialog. After logging into VPN (using my new pw), I restarted Outlook again and this time my credentials were accepted. I appear to be able to get into all the office apps now.
However, Box Sync is not running. I just tried to restart it but I continue to get taken to the single sign-in page and when I enter my credentials I get the “Page Expired” dialog.
On a possibly related note, I had a Microsoft account using my MSOE e-mail address before MSOE migrated to the hosted Outlook and the new “school or business” account option became available. I still have to use the business option when logging in. I’m wondering if this might be part of the problem. In fact, when I restarted my computer as describe above, I was prompted to enter my personal MS credentials. I saw something a few weeks ago regarding how to merge your MS accounts and may look into doing so.
I’ll likely be on campus and will try to bring my laptop to the helpdesk to see if you can figure anything out.
Dr. Tritt

helpdesk-note.body:
This is another message to Thomas regarding this problem. I sent the first last night and second earlier this morning.
My Box Sync login problem is resolved. Here is what I did (but I’m not completely sure which if any of these steps solved the problem). I deleted all pingidentity.com related cookies from Chrome and tried starting Box Sync again. I got the page expired dialog. I established a GlobalProtect VPN connection and then restarted my laptop. This was the second or third restart since my pw change. During the restart, I got a Box Sync login dialog but before responding to it I re-established a VPN connection. I was then successfully able to log into Box Sync.
I hope this information helps you figure out this problem.

helpdesk-ticket.description:
[cid:image001.png@01D1D6CE.01B4D3D0]
To increase security from active threats and zero day viruses, IT will be disabling macros in all Microsoft Office documents. This will protect users from accidentally installing malicious software that can encrypt their hard drive, and hold their data ransom.
With macros disabled, most users will not notice a difference in the way they use Microsoft Office documents. A few of you may find that this directly impacts your workflow. If you need access to macros, please contact the Helpdesk for additional options.
No MSOE employee nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask for your account password.

Hi Carole,
Last summer we started automating faculty, staff and students distribution lists based off of their information in Jenzabar. Since we've done this we can no longer manually update these lists. The only exception is if an faculty/staff need to be in two distribution lists we'd let the automated process add them to their main list and then using the exception rule we'd add them to the second list.
Since Dr. Rolland is in the Physics & Chemistry distribution list that means that his department in Jenzabar is set to Physics & Chemistry. Since IT cannot change employee records I suggest contacting HR and informing them of these inconsistencies.

helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Carole,

Last summer we started automating faculty, staff and students distribution lists based off of their information in Jenzabar.  Since we've done this we can no longer manually update these lists.  The only exception is if an faculty/staff need to be in two distribution lists we'd let the automated process add them to their main list and then using the exception rule we'd add them to the second list.

Since Dr. Rolland is in the Physics & Chemistry distribution list that means that his department in Jenzabar is set to Physics & Chemistry.  For Joshua Jaszewski his account is disabled, which usually means that he is no longer active in Jenzabar or his contract was not updated or expired in Jenzabar. 

Since IT cannot change employee records I suggest contacting HR and informing them of these inconsistencies.

Let me  know if you have any questions

Thanks
Mike Timm

Last summer we started automating faculty, staff and students distribution lists based off of their information in Jenzabar.  Since we've done this we can no longer manually update these lists.  The only exception is if an faculty/staff need to be in two distribution lists we'd let the automated process add them to their main list and then using the exception rule we'd add them to the second list.

Since Dr. Rolland is in the Physics & Chemistry distribution list that means that his department in Jenzabar is set to Physics & Chemistry.  For Joshua Jaszewski his account is disabled, which usually means that he is no longer active in Jenzabar or his contract was not updated or expired in Jenzabar. 

Since IT cannot change employee records I suggest contacting HR and informing them of these inconsistencies.

Let me  know if you have any questions

Thanks
Mike Timm

I have set your profile account type to "faculty/staff." Now you should be able to fill in your title, phone number, etc. in your profile as well as access employee sections of the Community.

Kent Peterson MSOE Marketing & Public Affairs (414) 277-7176 peterson@msoe.edu

helpdesk-note.body:
Cameron, route any questions or issues about setting user types to me. New users are automatically "prospective students" and if they are employees, we manually change them over to the correct user type and set their department. That way they see the sections of the Community they are supposed to see (different user types have different views).
Kent Peterson Marketing and Public Affairs (414) 277-7176 peterson@msoe.edu

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Setting up a new "A" Record
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Setting up this ticket on behalf of the Development Office. See Ted Fitzpatrick's email below for the details on what they are requesting. (Stelter is a third party provider of specialty web content related to planned giving).
From: Fitzpatrick, Edward Sent: Wednesday, July 06, 2016 1:46 PM To: Haugsland, Judith <haugsland@msoe.edu>; Kowalski, Jonathan <kowalski@msoe.edu> Cc: Everts, Sandra <everts@msoe.edu> Subject: Information for our web administrator Friends: Below is the information necessary for our web administrator to link our Stelter Planned Giving site to our main page. I’m copying Sandy Everts. Is Sandy now our web administrator? If not, then let me know who is and I’ll get this information to them. Thanks.
Instructions Our planned giving website is ready to go live. To complete this process, we need to: **Have our web administrator set up an "A Record" (not a "CNAME”) that points plannedgiving.msoe.edu and www. plannedgiving.msoe.edu to the following IP address on your server: 69.175.21.35. (Though www.subdomain.clientdomain.org is not widely used, it is a valid URL. We need to set this option up to ensure both variations of the domain work for your donors. Please note: The servers are configured to listen for specific host-names. As there is no direct website called ’69.175.21.35’ hosted on the web servers, attempting to enter this into the URL will result in a 404. URL Rewrites are utilized on the web server back end to ensure that web requests with the correct Host Header information will render the correct content.)
**Replace our current Planned Giving link with our new custom link: plannedgiving.msoe.edu. (Stelter recommends that it does not open in a new window.) Once Our website is linked, Stelter recommends that we use the web analytics tools to review site traffic reports at any time. Site traffic reports will be automatically delivered to you on a quarterly basis. Site analytics login information https://my.omniture.com/login/ Company Name = The Stelter Company Username = Milwaukee.School.Engineering Password = stelter0827 Version 15 To learn more about how to use the analytics, visit Stelter’s FAQ website: analyticsfaq.myplannedgift.org. Additional Reminder:
Royalty-Free Content: As part of our digital marketing platform package, we have access to Stelter’s Royalty-Free Content Library. These articles are attached and can be incorporated into any of our internal marketing and fundraising materials. Please let me know once our planned giving pages are linked and if you have any other questions.
Ted Fitzpatrick
Edward A. Fitzpatrick III Director of Planned Giving Milwaukee School of Engineering 1025 North Broadway Milwaukee, WI 53202 414- 277-7148 (direct) fitzpatrick@msoe.edu

From: Fitzpatrick, Edward 
Sent: Wednesday, July 06, 2016 1:46 PM
To: Haugsland, Judith <haugsland@msoe.edu>; Kowalski, Jonathan <kowalski@msoe.edu>
Cc: Everts, Sandra <everts@msoe.edu>
Subject: Information for our web administrator
Friends: Below is the information necessary for our web administrator to link our Stelter Planned Giving site to our main page. I’m copying Sandy Everts. Is Sandy now our web administrator? If not, then let me know who is and I’ll get this information to them. Thanks.
 
Instructions
 Our planned giving website is ready to go live. To complete this process, we need to:
 **Have our web administrator set up an "A Record" (not a "CNAME”) that points plannedgiving.msoe.edu and www. plannedgiving.msoe.edu to the following IP address on your server: 69.175.21.35.
 (Though www.subdomain.clientdomain.org is not widely used, it is a valid URL. We need to set this option up to ensure both variations of the domain work for your donors. Please note: The servers are configured to listen for specific host-names. As there is no direct website called ’69.175.21.35’ hosted on the web servers, attempting to enter this into the URL will result in a 404. URL Rewrites are utilized on the web server back end to ensure that web requests with the correct Host Header information will render the correct content.)
 
 **Replace our current Planned Giving link with our new custom link: plannedgiving.msoe.edu. (Stelter recommends that it does not open in a new window.)
 Once Our website is linked, Stelter recommends that we use the web analytics tools to review site traffic reports at any time. Site traffic reports will be automatically delivered to you on a quarterly basis.
 Site analytics login information
https://my.omniture.com/login/
Company Name = The Stelter Company
Username = Milwaukee.School.Engineering
Password = stelter0827
Version 15
 To learn more about how to use the analytics, visit Stelter’s FAQ website: analyticsfaq.myplannedgift.org.
 Additional Reminder:
 
 Royalty-Free Content: As part of our digital marketing platform package, we have access to Stelter’s Royalty-Free Content Library. These articles are attached and can be incorporated into any of our internal marketing and fundraising materials.
 Please let me know once our planned giving pages are linked and if you have any other questions.
Ted Fitzpatrick
 
Edward A. Fitzpatrick III
Director of Planned Giving
Milwaukee School of Engineering
1025 North Broadway
Milwaukee, WI 53202
414- 277-7148 (direct)
fitzpatrick@msoe.edu

Hi Benjamin Blacklock, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9472
Ok, I have attached the steps below to access the MSOE Community for the first time. Please let me know if they solve your issue.
1) Go to community.msoe.edu
2) On the top of the page, select "Register" 3) Select "Create An Account" 4) Select "I Have MSOE or Alumni Credentials" 5) Fill in the forms that appear. Make sure for your email and password you use your MSOE email address and password. This will link the Community Account to your MSOE account. Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi schaferd, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9524
According to my database you are not registered for classes in this coming fall quarter. IF you are not registered or enrolled in classes, your access to your MSOE account will be removed at the presented date. In order to keep your account active you need to register for classes in the fall. If you are not taking classes, but are working on a graduate paper, you should reach out to the registrar and they may be able to assist you. I will be marking this issue as resolved, however, if you have any questions or concerns please do not hesitate to contact us.
Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Jenzabar Double Check
helpdesk-ticket.description: Hello, We did a manual check for EFTs and it looks like Jenzabar took two checks and combined them into one check 900000005. When we tried to void the check it brings up an error message (most likely because there are two separate payments utilizing the same check number). Is there any way to get rid of this check? Thanks, Tom
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello,

We did a manual check for EFTs and it looks like Jenzabar took two checks and combined them into one check 900000005. When we tried to void the check it brings up an error message (most likely because there are two separate payments utilizing the same check number). Is there any way to get rid of this check?

Thanks,

Tom

helpdesk-note.body: From previous Jenzabar Support Answers: This error most often indicates that the check number being voided has been used before for a different vendor. In order to be able to void the check, the check number can only be assigned to one vendor. Work will need to be done behind the scenes to the following tables: CHK_RECONCILIATION, INVOICE_HEADER and TRANS_HIST. Typically a script is run to change the check number for the 'old' check that you are not voiding to a number such as 9991234 if the check number is 1234. Just add 999 to the beginning of the check number for the rows for one of the vendors to get those rows out of the way so that the check is then only attached to one vendor and can be voided. When updating chk_reconciliation, that will leave no row there for the actaul check you are going to void. So you will need to manually input that check via the Previous Checks window. Then void the check.
helpdesk-note.body-html: From previous Jenzabar Support Answers: This error most often indicates that the check number being voided has been used before for a different vendor. In order to be able to void the check, the check number can only be assigned to one vendor. Work will need to be done behind the scenes to the following tables: CHK_RECONCILIATION, INVOICE_HEADER and TRANS_HIST. Typically a script is run to change the check number for the 'old' check that you are not voiding to a number such as 9991234 if the check number is 1234. Just add 999 to the beginning of the check number for the rows for one of the vendors to get those rows out of the way so that the check is then only attached to one vendor and can be voided. When updating chk_reconciliation, that will leave no row there for the actaul check you are going to void. So you will need to manually input that check via the Previous Checks window. Then void the check.

helpdesk-note.body: Jenzabar Ticekt 356523: You can change the check number for the one vendor/invoice in INVOICE_HEADER and TRANS_HIST so the check can be voided. It will need to be done manually since there is not a window in EX that allows you to change this data.
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Jenzabar Ticekt 356523: You can change the check number for the one vendor/invoice in INVOICE_HEADER and TRANS_HIST so the check can be voided.
It will need to be done manually since there is not a window in EX that allows you to change this data.

Your Community account should work correctly now. When you log in, click the "My News" item in the menu, next you'll see a page with a row of icons across the top for most of the web-related resources you'll use as a student. There's an icon for email and this should get your to your MSOE email.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Derek Riley, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9569
The first error is most likely due to it opening while setup is still running in the background. As for setting up GlobalProtect, you should be able to go to View and select Advanced View. Now there should be a tab labeled Settings. Under this tab there will be three boxes; one for your username, one for your password and one for the server. The username and password are those associated with your MSOE account. The server is sslvpn.msoe.edu . Are you able to connect using this information? Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Connection Issue
helpdesk-ticket.description: I am unable to use my recently acquired Xbox due to a stricted NAT type - Xbox services seem to be blocked.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: I am unable to use my recently acquired Xbox due to a stricted NAT type - Xbox services seem to be blocked.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Hunter Parks, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9575
The Xbox One uses IPv6 networking, while the MSOE network runs off of IPv4. This can lead to some issues, however, multiple users have been able to get this setup to work. The network settings on your Xbox One and on your Router must be properly configured. I would recommend you look for assistance from Microsoft's website, as we do not officially support your Xbox One or its connection. As such, I will be marking this as resolved. I apologize for any inconvenience this causes you and please feel free to contact us with any additional questions or concerns. Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Hunter Parks, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/9605
We are unable to provide any additional hardware. However, I was able to dig up a list of possible solutions for your issue of having a strict NAT. Please let us know if any of these resolve your issue.
Recommend they add the XBO to the DMZ on their router, if they have one that allows DMZ addresses Enable UPNP to allow necessary ports to be available to the XBO (may require router and XBO reboot) Open the following ports (either do this or enable UPNP, not both): Port 88 (UDP) Port 3074 (UDP and TCP) Port 53 (UDP and TCP) Port 80 (TCP) Port 500 (UDP) UDP Port 3544 (UDP) UDP Port 4500 (UDP) Reset the MAC address of the XBO: Settings > network > Advanced settings > Alternate mac address > Clear
Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

Hi Hunter Parks, From the responses to this incident, there appears to be a solution. Any additional hardware you would need to make your xbox work would be your responsibility. Our support of this issue is limited to this set of instructions:
Recommend they add the XBO to the DMZ on their router, if they have one that allows DMZ addresses Enable UPNP to allow necessary ports to be available to the XBO (may require router and XBO reboot) Open the following ports (either do this or enable UPNP, not both): Port 88 (UDP) Port 3074 (UDP and TCP) Port 53 (UDP and TCP) Port 80 (TCP) Port 500 (UDP) UDP Port 3544 (UDP) UDP Port 4500 (UDP) Reset the MAC address of the XBO: Settings > network > Advanced settings > Alternate mac address > Clear
The Help Desk can provide instructions, advice, and encouragement on personally owned hardware. It has been reported to me that this set of instructions does work in our environment for the xboxOne. Please try again or continue to implement your solution.
With the information presented in the incident, I am going to consider this issue resolved.
Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202

Hello -
I am putting in a ticket for a repair to be done by Facilities - please let me know if I should be directing this email somewhere else.
As part of a recent floor repair to SG100. a small partition was removed that blocked off a 9.5" x 20" opening between the 'student activity area' and the main lab. It is on the west side of the inner overhead door, at floor level. There are a couple of metal conduits that run through the opening. Could you please close off this opening? A piece of 3/4" plywood with some brackets to hold it in place might work - I don't think we need anything fancy.
If this could be done by the end of August that would be great - if not, OK.
Let me know if you need more information.
Thanks -
Jeff

helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello -

I am putting in a ticket for a repair to be done by Facilities - please let me know if I should be directing this email somewhere else.

As part of a recent floor repair to SG100. a small partition was removed that blocked off a 9.5" x 20" opening between the 'student activity area' and the main lab.  It is on the west side of the inner overhead door, at floor level.  There are a couple of metal conduits that run through the opening.  Could you please close off this opening?  A piece of 3/4" plywood with some brackets to hold it in place might work - I don't think we need anything fancy.

If this could be done by the end of August that would be great - if not, OK.

Let me know if you need more information.

Thanks -

Jeff

Jeffrey A. MacDonald, MS
Lab Technician/Adjunct Associate Professor
Office: CC 34
Milwaukee School of Engineering
Civil and Architectural Engineering & Construction Management Department
1025 N. Broadway
Milwaukee, Wisconsin

macdonal@msoe.edu
(414) 277-2505
